22/04/2003
SKOPJE, Macedonia -- On Monday (21 April), Parliament Speaker Nikola Popovski urged the Democratic Party of Albanians (DPA) to return to parliament, following Saturday's announcement of a walkout.Popovski denied DPA allegations that implementation of the Ohrid peace accord is being stalled in parliament. 
He asked members to abandon what he called political manoeuvring and actively participate in efforts to realise the goals of the peace process.
At a joint press conference in Skopje, meanwhile, representatives of the EU, NATO and the OSCE stressed that all parties that signed the framework agreement, including the DPA, should assume political responsibility and engage actively in its implementation.
In other news, the opposition VMRO-DPMNE officially confirmed Monday that its leader, former Prime Minister Ljubco Georgievski, will not seek re-election at the party congress next month. 
VMRO-DPMNE Deputy Chief Nikola Gruevski reportedly is his likely successor.
Also Monday, the Macedonian government adopted an anti-corruption strategy. 
It is aimed at eliminating bureaucracy and nepotism, and at bolstering public trust in state institutions. 
(Utrinski Vesnik, Dnevnik - 22/04/03; MIA, A1 TV, Makfax - 21/04/03)
